WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.520 --> 00:00:06.120
Prof: This topic today
is really fun.

00:00:06.120 --> 00:00:10.190
I love the Acts of Paul and
Thecla.

00:00:10.190 --> 00:00:12.320
It is such a bizarre document.
 

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:16.192
I hope you read it before class
as the syllabus instructed you

00:00:16.192 --> 00:00:16.510
to.
 

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:19.574
It's not an easy document to
get into if it's the first time

00:00:19.574 --> 00:00:22.690
you've come across this kind of
non-canonical early Christian

00:00:22.690 --> 00:00:23.470
literature.
 

00:00:23.470 --> 00:00:25.659
Sometimes we'll call this stuff
"apocryphal"

00:00:25.659 --> 00:00:27.890
which is just the Greek word
for "hidden."

00:00:27.890 --> 00:00:33.357
This is not part of the
apocrypha that's published in

00:00:33.357 --> 00:00:37.145
your Bible,
your study Bible if you bought

00:00:37.145 --> 00:00:42.006
the Bible that I requested which
was the Oxford Study Bible with

00:00:42.006 --> 00:00:43.010
Apocrypha.
 

00:00:43.010 --> 00:00:46.623
That apocrypha,
as I explained at the beginning

00:00:46.623 --> 00:00:51.180
of the whole semester is Jewish
literature that was written

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:55.814
sometime in the Second Temple
period and it's not explicitly

00:00:55.814 --> 00:00:59.350
Christian literature for the
most part.

00:00:59.350 --> 00:01:02.789
When people talk about The
Apocrypha that's published in a

00:01:02.789 --> 00:01:05.141
modern Bible,
they're talking about that

00:01:05.141 --> 00:01:08.280
Jewish literature that survived
in Greek mainly.

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:12.712
In fact this is why those books
were rejected by the reformers

00:01:12.712 --> 00:01:15.909
Martin Luther and Calvin,
and Melanchthon.

00:01:15.909 --> 00:01:18.906
They tended to not use the
apocrypha in a Protestant Bible

00:01:18.906 --> 00:01:22.269
precisely because they wanted to
go back to the Hebrew Bible like

00:01:22.269 --> 00:01:24.846
the rabbis were using,
and so The Apocrypha,

00:01:24.846 --> 00:01:27.988
although it has continued to be
part of the Roman Catholic

00:01:27.988 --> 00:01:29.959
Bible,
and as something having a

00:01:29.959 --> 00:01:32.268
secondary status,
has not been part of the

00:01:32.268 --> 00:01:33.190
Protestant Bible.
 

00:01:33.190 --> 00:01:36.885
That term "apocrypha"
refers to that very varying

00:01:36.885 --> 00:01:40.516
list because what is actually
even included in that Jewish

00:01:40.516 --> 00:01:44.275
apocrypha varies according to
which publication you may pick

00:01:44.275 --> 00:01:44.849
up.
 

00:01:44.849 --> 00:01:48.575
Sometimes people will also use
this word "apocrypha"

00:01:48.575 --> 00:01:52.178
for what they call something
like New Testament apocrypha or

00:01:52.178 --> 00:01:54.010
early Christian apocrypha.
 

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:57.025
That's kind of a misleading
term because there's nothing

00:01:57.025 --> 00:01:59.110
hidden about this literature at
all.

00:01:59.110 --> 00:02:01.305
It's always been there,
it's just not part of the

00:02:01.305 --> 00:02:02.129
Christian canon.
 

00:02:02.129 --> 00:02:06.433
Some of it is entirely
orthodox, some of it is rather

00:02:06.433 --> 00:02:10.014
heretical,
and some of it is somewhere not

00:02:10.014 --> 00:02:14.461
completely in tune with later
orthodoxy but nevertheless

00:02:14.461 --> 00:02:19.150
reflecting what was definitely
orthodox in its own day.

00:02:19.150 --> 00:02:22.000
All this literature is written
in the second century,

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:23.926
our document today,
the Acts of Paul and

00:02:23.926 --> 00:02:26.181
Thecla,
was composed in the second

00:02:26.181 --> 00:02:29.778
century and it was considered
quite good literature by many

00:02:29.778 --> 00:02:31.020
early Christians.
 

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:34.901
It just wasn't part of the New
Testament, mainly because people

00:02:34.901 --> 00:02:38.658
knew it was a bit later of a
document, not so much because of

00:02:38.658 --> 00:02:40.348
concerns for orthodoxy.
 

00:02:40.348 --> 00:02:43.960
One of the purposes of my
teaching this course,

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:47.169
one of my purposes of teaching
all of my courses,

00:02:47.169 --> 00:02:53.280
is to get students to start
thinking completely differently.

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:54.794
In other words,
you've noticed,

00:02:54.794 --> 00:02:57.503
perhaps,
that one of the things I stress

00:02:57.503 --> 00:03:00.908
in my lectures is how odd the
ancient world is,

00:03:00.908 --> 00:03:04.653
even how odd early Christianity
is from what most of us tend to

00:03:04.653 --> 00:03:05.438
come at it.
 

00:03:05.438 --> 00:03:08.425
This is because I teach New
Testament studies and the

00:03:08.425 --> 00:03:11.639
history of early Christianity
almost like ethnography.

00:03:11.639 --> 00:03:14.574
I try to get you to imagine
yourself coming into a culture

00:03:14.574 --> 00:03:17.560
that's really different from the
culture you grew up in.

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:21.955
This is something I think is
basic to religious studies as a

00:03:21.955 --> 00:03:25.443
discipline,
and religious studies teaches

00:03:25.443 --> 00:03:29.318
you to look at some kind of
group of people,

00:03:29.318 --> 00:03:32.455
or an activity,
or a belief structure that

00:03:32.455 --> 00:03:35.818
seems to you initially
absolutely bizarre.

00:03:35.818 --> 00:03:39.032
And you think,
how could any rational person

00:03:39.032 --> 00:03:39.780
do that?
 

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:42.030
How can any rational person
belief that?

00:03:42.030 --> 00:03:46.702
To keep looking at it seriously
and to look at it with enough

00:03:46.702 --> 00:03:50.907
sympathy that you actually can
see eventually how it is

00:03:50.907 --> 00:03:52.699
perfectly rational.
 

00:03:52.699 --> 00:03:56.378
This document today is a great
place to illustrate that,

00:03:56.378 --> 00:03:59.229
because whenever I teach this
document to people your age,

00:03:59.229 --> 00:04:01.810
eighteen to twenty-two year old
college students,

00:04:01.810 --> 00:04:04.520
if you read this carefully and
you get into this stuff,

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:06.560
it should be bizarre to you.
 

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:11.536
This document depicts young
people who are attracted to a

00:04:11.536 --> 00:04:16.779
version of Christianity that
forbids having sex entirely.

00:04:16.779 --> 00:04:19.740
It's completely ascetic.
 

00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:22.101
The Paul in the Acts of Paul
and Thecla says,

00:04:22.101 --> 00:04:24.879
if you have sex you're probably
not going to go to heaven.

00:04:24.879 --> 00:04:29.271
Basically the gospel mentioned
in this document is continence,

00:04:29.271 --> 00:04:32.439
by which this document means
avoiding sex.

00:04:32.439 --> 00:04:36.790
And that's going to be bizarre
enough because people in the

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:39.639
modern world kind of have the
idea,

00:04:39.639 --> 00:04:44.154
well why would somebody join
any movement that forbade sexual

00:04:44.154 --> 00:04:45.660
intimacy entirely?
 

00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:48.190
What kind of draw did that have
for people?

00:04:48.190 --> 00:04:50.379
Why did that gospel succeed?
 

00:04:50.379 --> 00:04:53.449
What may be surprising to you
is it did succeed.

00:04:53.449 --> 00:04:55.620
In the ancient world a lot of
people,

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:58.240
especially it seems sometimes
even young people,

00:04:58.240 --> 00:05:02.271
were drawn to early
Christianity precisely because

00:05:02.271 --> 00:05:03.670
it was ascetic.
 

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:07.415
It taught this radical
asceticism of watching what you

00:05:07.415 --> 00:05:11.281
eat and especially avoiding sex,
or if not avoiding sex

00:05:11.281 --> 00:05:14.824
entirely, severely limiting
sexual intercourse and sexual

00:05:14.824 --> 00:05:15.709
attraction.
 

00:05:15.709 --> 00:05:18.750
\What is it about the ancient
culture,

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:22.379
what is it about these people
that caused them not only to be

00:05:22.379 --> 00:05:26.009
converted to Christianity but to
be converted especially to a

00:05:26.009 --> 00:05:28.550
form of it that was radically
ascetic?

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:31.829
In order to see why that kind
of Christianity was--because

00:05:31.829 --> 00:05:35.110
that's the actual kind of
Christianity that was successful

00:05:35.110 --> 00:05:36.550
in the ancient world.
 

00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:40.100
If you were listening to most
modern American Christians,

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:43.617
modern American people
generally, what are the two most

00:05:43.617 --> 00:05:47.071
important teachings about
Christianity in the minds of

00:05:47.071 --> 00:05:48.310
most Americans?
 

00:05:48.310 --> 00:05:52.310
The family, the importance of
the family,

00:05:52.310 --> 00:05:55.670
and by that they mean the
heterosexual nuclear family,

00:05:55.670 --> 00:05:58.819
but even the liberal churches
which are willing to recognize

00:05:58.819 --> 00:06:02.190
gay relationships,
they still construe that as gay

00:06:02.190 --> 00:06:06.040
marriage or just gay versions of
the nuclear family.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:08.245
The family is the most
important thing about

00:06:08.245 --> 00:06:10.810
Christianity in the minds of a
lot of Americans.

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:13.620
The second thing is
nationalism, patriotism.

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:18.271
If you took away patriotism and
nationalism, and the family out

00:06:18.271 --> 00:06:21.648
of Christianity,
most people in modern America

00:06:21.648 --> 00:06:24.199
wouldn't recognize it as such.
 

00:06:24.199 --> 00:06:27.132
What's odd is that,
when you read these ancient

00:06:27.132 --> 00:06:30.894
documents, that's precisely the
two things that Christianity

00:06:30.894 --> 00:06:31.660
attacks.
 

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:35.464
This form of early Christianity
was anti-family,

00:06:35.464 --> 00:06:39.269
for the most part,
and it was anti-patriotic.

00:06:39.269 --> 00:06:44.004
The people who say,
but this is traditional

00:06:44.004 --> 00:06:47.339
Christianity,
those people don't know their

00:06:47.339 --> 00:06:50.168
history before 1950,
because the church,

00:06:50.168 --> 00:06:55.350
the overall Christian churches
were never pro-family for the

00:06:55.350 --> 00:06:58.600
first 1500 years of its
existence.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:01.810
The Roman Catholic Church,
up until the Reformation,

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:04.120
always had as its official
position,

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:07.901
not just popular ideas,
its official position was

00:07:07.901 --> 00:07:10.740
celibacy is superior to
sexuality.

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:14.160
If you have to have sex,
if you can't control yourself

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:17.966
you're allowed to get married
and have sex within the bounds

00:07:17.966 --> 00:07:19.000
of marriage.
 

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.216
But the better thing,
the better virtue would be to

00:07:22.216 --> 00:07:24.920
avoid sex entirely for your
entire life.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:28.920
The next best thing is to have
sex if you need just to make

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:30.663
babies,
but then as soon as you have

00:07:30.663 --> 00:07:33.516
your babies,
stop having sex and be ascetic

00:07:33.516 --> 00:07:35.300
the rest of your life.
 

00:07:35.300 --> 00:07:38.911
If your spouse dies,
you are permitted to get

00:07:38.911 --> 00:07:40.797
remarried,
most of the time,

00:07:40.797 --> 00:07:43.490
but the higher virtue would be
in remaining unmarried and

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:45.800
remaining celibate for the rest
of your life.

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:49.225
That was considered the
doctrine in Christianity,

00:07:49.225 --> 00:07:52.793
at least up until the
Reformation, so the sixteenth

00:07:52.793 --> 00:07:53.649
century.
 

00:07:53.649 --> 00:07:55.982
When people talk about
"traditional family

00:07:55.982 --> 00:07:58.720
values" being traditionally
the Christian way,

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:02.309
they're not talking about
Christianity as it existed from

00:08:02.309 --> 00:08:05.769
the time of Jesus all the way up
until around 1600,

00:08:05.769 --> 00:08:09.980
and even then from 1600 until
1950,

00:08:09.980 --> 00:08:13.184
the ideal form in most
Christianity was not the nuclear

00:08:13.184 --> 00:08:15.319
family but some kind of
household.

00:08:15.319 --> 00:08:18.185
In Puritan New England,
people didn't live in little

00:08:18.185 --> 00:08:21.286
nuclear families--
townships, the New Haven

00:08:21.286 --> 00:08:24.500
Colony, the Massachusetts Bay
Colony,

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:28.105
they were organized into
households that were run by the

00:08:28.105 --> 00:08:31.379
male head of household,
his wife under him,

00:08:31.379 --> 00:08:35.043
children under that,
servants and other free people

00:08:35.043 --> 00:08:38.301
often living in the household
also or connected to the

00:08:38.301 --> 00:08:39.100
household.
 

00:08:39.100 --> 00:08:41.658
If you are, for example,
an adult male,

00:08:41.658 --> 00:08:44.590
twenty-five years old in New
England,

00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:47.820
in Puritan New England,
and you weren't married,

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:51.408
you weren't really supposed to
live alone or with other men.

00:08:51.408 --> 00:08:54.629
That happens sometimes,
but the town fathers--

00:08:54.629 --> 00:08:58.538
and these colonies were ruled
as communities,

00:08:58.538 --> 00:09:02.057
not individual people--the town
fathers would want to put you

00:09:02.057 --> 00:09:05.363
into somebody else's household,
into the household of another

00:09:05.363 --> 00:09:05.590
man.
 

00:09:05.590 --> 00:09:09.120
They certainly wouldn't let
women, adult women live

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:10.038
separately.
 

00:09:10.038 --> 00:09:12.649
Notice, this is not
individualism in the modern

00:09:12.649 --> 00:09:15.942
sense, and it's not the nuclear
family in the modern sense,

00:09:15.942 --> 00:09:18.269
these are extended family
households.

00:09:18.269 --> 00:09:21.528
That was the New England
Protestant way.

00:09:21.528 --> 00:09:26.344
When did the idea that the best
form of the family was the

00:09:26.344 --> 00:09:30.990
nuclear family come about in
popular culture overall?

00:09:30.990 --> 00:09:32.668
The 1950s.
 

00:09:32.668 --> 00:09:36.839
When people talk about that
being the Christian thing

00:09:36.839 --> 00:09:41.409
they're forgetting the vast
sweep of Christian history.

00:09:41.409 --> 00:09:43.269
They're just ignoring it.
 

00:09:43.269 --> 00:09:47.270
This document is a good place
to see why that made sense for

00:09:47.270 --> 00:09:49.317
people,
especially in the ancient

00:09:49.317 --> 00:09:51.719
world, and to make it--
since for the Middle Ages and

00:09:51.719 --> 00:09:54.009
all the rest of the time you'll
have to take another course.

00:09:54.009 --> 00:09:57.788
One of the things I want you to
do is enter into this text as if

00:09:57.788 --> 00:10:01.129
you're an ethnographer,
an anthropologist and try to

00:10:01.129 --> 00:10:04.750
see how does this make sense,
how does this gospel that this

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:07.429
text proclaimed,
how did it make sense to people

00:10:07.429 --> 00:10:09.340
and why was it so wildly
popular,

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:12.990
because it was wildly popular.
 

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:16.269
First, you have to know a bit
about the Greco-Roman novel.

00:10:16.269 --> 00:10:18.432
I talked about this early in
the semester when we talked

00:10:18.432 --> 00:10:19.730
about the Acts of the Apostles.
 

00:10:19.730 --> 00:10:23.096
Greek novels are very
interesting, there are six of

00:10:23.096 --> 00:10:25.590
them that survive in almost
whole,

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:27.440
and in fragments of a lot of
others,

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.120
and you can find these in the
English translation.

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:34.678
Help me out teaching fellows,
what's the name of the

00:10:34.678 --> 00:10:37.629
collection of the Greek novels?
 

00:10:37.629 --> 00:10:40.436
It's called something like
Collected Greek Novels,

00:10:40.436 --> 00:10:40.779
yes.
 

00:10:40.779 --> 00:10:44.850
Reardon is the editor:
R-E-A-R-D-O-N.

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:48.413
If you want to dip into these
just get the collected ancient

00:10:48.413 --> 00:10:51.980
novels - edited by Reardon and
read through some of them.

00:10:51.980 --> 00:10:53.720
They're very entertaining.
 

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:56.070
One of the things that the
typical plot is,

00:10:56.070 --> 00:11:00.058
a woman of high elite status,
these are--

00:11:00.058 --> 00:11:03.048
these usually are people--young
people of elite families--

00:11:03.048 --> 00:11:05.750
they're usually set in
classical Greece although

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:08.450
they're not written until the
first century,

00:11:08.450 --> 00:11:10.389
second century,
third century of our era,

00:11:10.389 --> 00:11:13.340
but they're often set in a more
classical Greek setting.

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:16.687
They are upper class people:
a young woman who's of an upper

00:11:16.687 --> 00:11:20.148
class family falls in love with
a young man who's also from an

00:11:20.148 --> 00:11:22.884
upper class family,
and in a few of the Greek

00:11:22.884 --> 00:11:26.350
novels they actually get married
and have a little honeymoon,

00:11:26.350 --> 00:11:28.710
a brief honeymoon period,
and then all hell breaks loose

00:11:28.710 --> 00:11:29.740
and something happens.
 

00:11:29.740 --> 00:11:32.743
In some cases they don't even
get to consummate their love yet

00:11:32.743 --> 00:11:34.269
because something intervenes.
 

00:11:34.269 --> 00:11:36.990
Usually what happens is a
disaster strikes.

00:11:36.990 --> 00:11:39.990
In one--I think I mentioned
this to you,

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:43.019
by Chariton,
Chaereas and Callirhoe,

00:11:43.019 --> 00:11:47.629
in one the husband gets jealous
thinking that his wife has had

00:11:47.629 --> 00:11:50.503
an affair he--
in a fit of rage--he kicks her,

00:11:50.503 --> 00:11:53.080
she falls over and everybody
thinks she's dead.

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:55.491
So he's grieving and grieving
because of course he's still

00:11:55.491 --> 00:11:56.548
madly in love with her.
 

00:11:56.548 --> 00:11:58.190
They're both madly in love with
each other.

00:11:58.190 --> 00:12:01.707
But they bury her in the tomb,
the big family tomb that's on

00:12:01.707 --> 00:12:03.200
the shore by the water.
 

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:05.681
Of course like--and Shakespeare
stole mercilessly from these

00:12:05.681 --> 00:12:07.826
kinds of things--
she wakes up in the tomb after

00:12:07.826 --> 00:12:10.340
they've already sealed the tomb
and she can't get out,

00:12:10.340 --> 00:12:12.570
and she says,
woe is me, they've buried me,

00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:15.788
I will never see my loved one.
 

00:12:15.788 --> 00:12:19.775
Pirates, who happened to be
outside, there were always

00:12:19.775 --> 00:12:23.009
pirates in these things,
lots of pirates.

00:12:23.009 --> 00:12:25.942
Pirates happened to be outside,
they hear her crying,

00:12:25.942 --> 00:12:27.690
and they break into the tomb.
 

00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:30.090
They were just going to do a
little tomb robbery,

00:12:30.090 --> 00:12:32.100
they were just attempting a
tomb robbery,

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:35.196
but they find this living
maiden--not maiden anymore she's

00:12:35.196 --> 00:12:38.149
had sex now so she's a maid,
not a maiden anymore.

00:12:38.149 --> 00:12:40.229
Anyway a beautiful young woman
and they decide,

00:12:40.229 --> 00:12:42.897
well great this--we can get
more for her than from the stuff

00:12:42.897 --> 00:12:43.440
in here.
 

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:46.860
We'll kidnap her,
sell her as into slavery at

00:12:46.860 --> 00:12:48.259
some other port.
 

00:12:48.259 --> 00:12:49.658
And they do.
 

00:12:49.658 --> 00:12:52.605
So they take her off,
they take her around over to

00:12:52.605 --> 00:12:54.529
Asia Minor, modern day Turkey.
 

00:12:54.529 --> 00:12:57.110
And there they sell her to this
