side of this sometimes.
 

00:37:56.869 --> 00:37:59.860
What is the opposition to
Paul's gospel?

00:37:59.860 --> 00:38:03.000
It's not men versus women,
right?

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.360
What is the opposition?
 

00:38:05.360 --> 00:38:10.376
It's male heads of households
against everybody else who would

00:38:10.376 --> 00:38:13.010
be members of their household.
 

00:38:13.010 --> 00:38:17.545
The people who opposed Paul the
most in this text are male heads

00:38:17.545 --> 00:38:20.552
of households,
precisely because they

00:38:20.552 --> 00:38:25.574
recognize that challenging the
centrality of sex and childbirth

00:38:25.574 --> 00:38:29.219
will in itself challenge their
households.

00:38:29.219 --> 00:38:31.521
In their system,
you have to have sex and

00:38:31.521 --> 00:38:34.860
childbirth in order to maintain
the household structure.

00:38:34.860 --> 00:38:37.164
They're the ones who are
against Paul,

00:38:37.164 --> 00:38:40.340
so Paul appeals mostly to women
and young people.

00:38:40.340 --> 00:38:43.204
I already think--I read part of
that in paragraph 7,

00:38:43.204 --> 00:38:46.690
"The women and the virgins
are going to hear him."

00:38:46.690 --> 00:38:52.032
In paragraph 9 it talks about
women and young people going to

00:38:52.032 --> 00:38:56.219
him and are talking to him,
so that's who it.

00:38:56.219 --> 00:39:01.909
Then in 12, I read this passage
in paragraph 12,

00:39:01.909 --> 00:39:05.103
"He deprives young men of
wives and maidens of

00:39:05.103 --> 00:39:07.916
husbands,"
so he's depriving the men who

00:39:07.916 --> 00:39:11.878
want to continue the household
structure and that's why they're

00:39:11.878 --> 00:39:13.219
opposed to him.
 

00:39:13.219 --> 00:39:26.547
Notice paragraph 26 and 27:
this guy sees Thecla in a

00:39:26.547 --> 00:39:36.286
different place,
Alexander sees Thecla,

00:39:36.286 --> 00:39:45.000
and he falls in love with her.
 

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:47.932
As is typical in these kinds of
texts, there's always a

00:39:47.932 --> 00:39:50.159
beautiful woman,
no man can resist her.

00:39:50.159 --> 00:39:54.619
He says he wants to marry her:
"I did not wish to marry

00:39:54.619 --> 00:39:56.079
Thamyris, I've been cast out of
the city ...

00:39:56.079 --> 00:39:58.835
Taking hold of Alexander [so
here she takes hold of this

00:39:58.835 --> 00:40:00.590
Alexander]
she ripped his cloak,

00:40:00.590 --> 00:40:03.331
took off the crown from his
head and made him a laughing

00:40:03.331 --> 00:40:03.730
stock.
 

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:06.510
But he, partly out of love for
her and partly in shame at what

00:40:06.510 --> 00:40:08.286
had befallen him,
brought her before the

00:40:08.286 --> 00:40:08.880
governor.
 

00:40:08.880 --> 00:40:11.177
And when she confessed that she
had done these things he

00:40:11.177 --> 00:40:12.429
condemned her to the beasts.
 

00:40:12.429 --> 00:40:15.117
But the women were panic
stricken and cried out before

00:40:15.117 --> 00:40:17.349
the judgment seat,
"An evil judgment!

00:40:17.349 --> 00:40:18.230
A godless judgment!"
 

00:40:18.230 --> 00:40:20.766
But Thecla asked the governor
that she might remain pure until

00:40:20.766 --> 00:40:22.179
she was to fight with the beast.
 

00:40:22.179 --> 00:40:24.170
[In other words she says;
just don't make me have sex.

00:40:24.170 --> 00:40:26.420
I'll be glad to go into the
arena and fight with the beast,

00:40:26.420 --> 00:40:29.789
just don't make me have sex.]
A rich woman named Tryphaena,

00:40:29.789 --> 00:40:30.387
whose wife [correction:
husband]

00:40:30.387 --> 00:40:31.519
had died,
took her under her protection

00:40:31.519 --> 00:40:32.110
and found comfort.
 

00:40:32.110 --> 00:40:34.974
When the beasts were led in
procession they bound her to a

00:40:34.974 --> 00:40:36.885
fierce lioness,
and the Queen Tryphaena

00:40:36.885 --> 00:40:37.739
followed her.
 

00:40:37.739 --> 00:40:40.561
And as Thecla sat upon her
back, the lioness licked her

00:40:40.561 --> 00:40:42.860
feet, and all the crowed was
amazed."

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:46.521
You have this situation
where--what's the problem with

00:40:46.521 --> 00:40:47.349
Alexander?
 

00:40:47.349 --> 00:40:48.980
He's shamed.
 

00:40:48.980 --> 00:40:51.356
So in this honor/shame system
of the ancient world,

00:40:51.356 --> 00:40:53.971
this is also an important
point: male heads of household

00:40:53.971 --> 00:40:55.539
occupy the position of honor.
 

00:40:55.539 --> 00:40:59.139
By tearing his clothes,
by knocking his crown off,

00:40:59.139 --> 00:41:02.170
she shames him in public,
and this of course totally

00:41:02.170 --> 00:41:05.320
disrupts this hierarchy of the
man over the woman,

00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:07.260
and that's part of what's going
on here.

00:41:07.260 --> 00:41:10.288
Women who refuse their role as
child bearers,

00:41:10.288 --> 00:41:13.315
as sex objects,
shame the men who put them in

00:41:13.315 --> 00:41:14.280
that role.
 

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:18.400
And so that's what the conflict
is about, shaming men and

00:41:18.400 --> 00:41:21.639
rebelling against the household
structure.

00:41:21.639 --> 00:41:24.579
Then of course there's the
solidarity of women with

00:41:24.579 --> 00:41:25.579
everybody else.
 

00:41:25.579 --> 00:41:28.992
Notice in this,
Paul himself is rather

00:41:28.992 --> 00:41:30.929
ambiguously placed.
 

00:41:30.929 --> 00:41:31.809
He's a man.
 

00:41:31.809 --> 00:41:35.280
What is Paul's role in all of
this?

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:38.916
I think it's interesting that
Paul doesn't come across in this

00:41:38.916 --> 00:41:42.255
text, at least in my reading,
as being a totally positive

00:41:42.255 --> 00:41:43.090
character.
 

00:41:43.090 --> 00:41:44.806
It praises him,
of course, and presents him as

00:41:44.806 --> 00:41:45.380
a man of God.
 

00:41:45.380 --> 00:41:47.820
But notice some of the things
that Paul does.

00:41:47.820 --> 00:41:50.880
Paul refuses to baptize her.
 

00:41:50.880 --> 00:41:53.909
Remember, she has to baptize
herself.

00:41:53.909 --> 00:41:57.329
This is that wonderful scene
where she's being martyred--

00:41:57.329 --> 00:41:58.489
they're trying to martyr her
again,

00:41:58.489 --> 00:42:02.291
and they strip her naked,
and then they have this big vat

00:42:02.291 --> 00:42:07.820
of killer man-eating seals--
yes that's what it says.

00:42:07.820 --> 00:42:11.835
You probably didn't even know
there were man-eating seals,

00:42:11.835 --> 00:42:15.500
but there were in the ancient
Mediterranean world.

00:42:15.500 --> 00:42:19.101
Instead of waiting to be thrown
into the vat of man eating

00:42:19.101 --> 00:42:20.896
seals,
a lightning bolt comes out of

00:42:20.896 --> 00:42:22.032
the sky,
strikes the water,

00:42:22.032 --> 00:42:24.480
all the man-eating seals die,
so God saves her.

00:42:24.480 --> 00:42:27.905
And then, though,
not to let the scene finish

00:42:27.905 --> 00:42:29.268
she--
she's all right,

00:42:29.268 --> 00:42:31.572
there's water,
she's asked Paul to baptize her

00:42:31.572 --> 00:42:35.632
once and he wouldn't do it,
so she throws herself into the

00:42:35.632 --> 00:42:37.940
water and baptizes herself.
 

00:42:37.940 --> 00:42:39.139
This is a woman!
 

00:42:39.139 --> 00:42:41.489
You're not supposed to let
women go around baptizing

00:42:41.489 --> 00:42:42.090
themselves!
 

00:42:42.090 --> 00:42:44.949
That could just disrupt all
kinds of stuff.

00:42:44.949 --> 00:42:48.362
Paul, at one point,
says he doesn't even know her

00:42:48.362 --> 00:42:49.429
in one place.
 

00:42:49.429 --> 00:42:50.920
He refuses to baptize her.
 

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:52.920
And Paul gets in trouble.
 

00:42:52.920 --> 00:42:54.760
He runs off and hides in caves
and stuff.

00:42:54.760 --> 00:42:57.449
Who's the big hero of this
story?

00:42:57.449 --> 00:42:58.570
It's not Paul.
 

00:42:58.570 --> 00:43:02.139
He's one of the heroes
but it's really Thecla.

00:43:02.139 --> 00:43:07.034
It's this woman who totally
refuses to accept her role as a

00:43:07.034 --> 00:43:08.300
baby factory.
 

00:43:08.300 --> 00:43:11.570
And that's what women are in
the ancient world,

00:43:11.570 --> 00:43:12.780
baby factories.
 

00:43:12.780 --> 00:43:14.768
She totally refuses to accept
that role.

00:43:14.768 --> 00:43:18.039
She baptizes herself when Paul
hesitates to baptize her.

00:43:18.039 --> 00:43:20.355
And then of course at the very
end of the document,

00:43:20.355 --> 00:43:21.420
remember how it ends?
 

00:43:21.420 --> 00:43:24.110
She goes to Paul and she says
she wants to be a follower of

00:43:24.110 --> 00:43:26.289
his, and he kind of--again he
kind of just says,

00:43:26.289 --> 00:43:27.449
no go leave me alone.
 

00:43:27.449 --> 00:43:30.380
Paul is not all that great with
her.

00:43:30.380 --> 00:43:32.139
What does she do?
 

00:43:32.139 --> 00:43:33.829
First she inherits a bunch of
money;

00:43:33.829 --> 00:43:36.380
another rich woman left her a
ton of money,

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:39.420
so she's able to support
herself and her mother.

00:43:39.420 --> 00:43:41.527
I guess she and her mother,
by the end of the thing,

00:43:41.527 --> 00:43:42.518
are now on good terms.
 

00:43:42.518 --> 00:43:45.391
I mean if you survive
lightening and man-eating seals,

00:43:45.391 --> 00:43:48.045
and God saves you,
maybe your mother will like you

00:43:48.045 --> 00:43:50.159
better and let you not get
married.

00:43:50.159 --> 00:43:52.842
She supports herself
financially through an

00:43:52.842 --> 00:43:55.652
inheritance that she gets from
another woman,

00:43:55.652 --> 00:43:57.570
and then what does she do?
 

00:43:57.570 --> 00:44:00.465
She cuts her hair short,
she dresses like a man,

00:44:00.465 --> 00:44:02.559
she actually becomes an
Apostle.

00:44:02.559 --> 00:44:06.284
She goes off to spread the
message of this ascetic,

00:44:06.284 --> 00:44:08.148
sex avoiding,
anti-family,

00:44:08.148 --> 00:44:11.800
anti-household gospel that she
got from Paul.

00:44:11.800 --> 00:44:16.730
Thecla becomes her own Apostle
spreading the message.

00:44:16.730 --> 00:44:19.659
Notice what kind of gospel
she's going around teaching.

00:44:19.659 --> 00:44:22.137
This is not pro-family,
this is not patriotic,

00:44:22.137 --> 00:44:23.570
this is not nationalism.
 

00:44:23.570 --> 00:44:27.760
This is putting all your eggs
in the basket of the kingdom of

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:28.179
God.
 

00:44:28.179 --> 00:44:30.880
That's the only thing worth
living for, is the kingdom of

00:44:30.880 --> 00:44:31.170
God.
 

00:44:31.170 --> 00:44:33.320
How do you get into the kingdom
of God?

00:44:33.320 --> 00:44:36.063
By avoiding sex and avoiding
the household,

00:44:36.063 --> 00:44:39.070
that's how you get in and
enjoy--and remain.

00:44:39.070 --> 00:44:40.469
How do you avoid death?
 

00:44:40.469 --> 00:44:43.960
By being resurrected.
 

00:44:43.960 --> 00:44:46.969
This message is a very erotic
message, in a sense.

00:44:46.969 --> 00:44:49.829
It's not getting sexual
eroticism or sexual desire and

00:44:49.829 --> 00:44:51.610
throwing it all out the window.
 

00:44:51.610 --> 00:44:55.896
It's actually using eroticism
and the appeal to beauty,

00:44:55.896 --> 00:45:00.344
and the appeal of sexual
desire, and it's capitalizing on

00:45:00.344 --> 00:45:00.900
it.
 

00:45:00.900 --> 00:45:04.849
The author is trying to get
you, as a young person who's

00:45:04.849 --> 00:45:08.282
afraid about death,
to convert to a message of the

00:45:08.282 --> 00:45:12.052
gospel that will liberate you
from the cycle of corruption and

00:45:12.052 --> 00:45:15.204
death,
that you will get into if you

00:45:15.204 --> 00:45:18.697
agree to go along with sex,
birth, death,

00:45:18.697 --> 00:45:23.050
decay, and that's what you do
if you choose the household.

00:45:23.050 --> 00:45:25.679
It's a radical document.
 

00:45:25.679 --> 00:45:30.250
Now the question is,
is this a feminist document?

00:45:30.250 --> 00:45:32.159
It's a good question.
 

00:45:32.159 --> 00:45:34.940
Its raises Thecla up even above
Paul,

00:45:34.940 --> 00:45:38.320
and it gives a message of
liberation to women,

00:45:38.320 --> 00:45:42.186
at least from whatever it is
that keeps them down at the

00:45:42.186 --> 00:45:43.826
time,
which is the patriarchal

00:45:43.826 --> 00:45:44.320
household.
 

00:45:44.320 --> 00:45:46.510
It gives them a way out of that.
 

00:45:46.510 --> 00:45:49.726
This is one of the reasons that
there are a lot of women in the

00:45:49.726 --> 00:45:52.760
ancient world who became nuns,
who wanted to avoid the

00:45:52.760 --> 00:45:56.210
household, and you had women
running away from their husbands

00:45:56.210 --> 00:45:57.130
all the time.
 

00:45:57.130 --> 00:45:58.739
Church leaders talk about it.
 

00:45:58.739 --> 00:45:59.860
Why?
 

00:45:59.860 --> 00:46:02.387
Because that was--you had to
get out of the household if you

00:46:02.387 --> 00:46:04.659
wanted to have any kind of
independence or liberty.

00:46:04.659 --> 00:46:07.757
If you wanted to have any kind
of exercise of power you had to

00:46:07.757 --> 00:46:09.889
get out of the male dominated
household.

00:46:09.889 --> 00:46:12.092
So Christianity,
the whole strain of

00:46:12.092 --> 00:46:15.869
Christianity appealed to
precisely those kinds of people,

00:46:15.869 --> 00:46:18.762
and the author is trying to get
you as a young person to make

00:46:18.762 --> 00:46:19.679
that choice also.
 

00:46:19.679 --> 00:46:24.199
Now the big question is do you
think it's feminist?

00:46:24.199 --> 00:46:27.661
Is this feminism or is there
something wrong with thinking

00:46:27.661 --> 00:46:29.059
about it as feminism?
 

00:46:29.059 --> 00:46:32.367
If you're writing a paper this
week maybe you can talk about

00:46:32.367 --> 00:46:32.760
that.
 

00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:37.523
Another big question is,
do you think this author is

00:46:37.523 --> 00:46:41.539
actually attacking the Pastoral
Epistles?

00:46:41.539 --> 00:46:45.250
Are the Pastoral Epistles
attacking this author?

00:46:45.250 --> 00:46:49.826
They are presenting two
diametrically opposed versions

00:46:49.826 --> 00:46:50.690
of Paul.
 

00:46:50.690 --> 00:46:52.550
They both claim Paul as their
author.

00:46:52.550 --> 00:46:55.452
They both claim to be
representing Paul's gospel,

00:46:55.452 --> 00:46:56.480
Paul's message.
 

00:46:56.480 --> 00:46:59.728
But one of them is very
pro-household,

00:46:59.728 --> 00:47:03.239
and marriage,
and sex, and childbirth;

00:47:03.239 --> 00:47:06.777
and the other is anti-marriage,
anti-household,

00:47:06.777 --> 00:47:09.239
anti-childbirth,
and anti-sex.

00:47:09.239 --> 00:47:12.539
They both claim Paul as the
author of their gospel.

00:47:12.539 --> 00:47:13.840
Do they know each other?
 

00:47:13.840 --> 00:47:15.349
That's the interesting
historical question.

00:47:15.349 --> 00:47:19.300
Or is it just by accident that
we have these two very radically

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:21.530
different appropriations of
Paul?

00:47:21.530 --> 00:47:24.574
All of those questions I hope
you'll talk about in your

00:47:24.574 --> 00:47:26.659
discussion groups later this
week,

00:47:26.659 --> 00:47:29.976
and if you're writing papers,
push yourself to answer some

00:47:29.976 --> 00:47:31.780
big questions in your papers.
 

00:47:31.780 --> 00:47:32.960
Any questions?
 

00:47:32.960 --> 00:47:34.440
Yes.
 

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:36.844
Student:  Is it possible
or conceivable that a woman

00:47:36.844 --> 00:47:37.840
would have written it?
 

00:47:37.840 --> 00:47:39.916
Prof: Is it possible or
conceivable that a woman would

00:47:39.916 --> 00:47:40.539
have written it?
 

00:47:40.539 --> 00:47:41.989
It's completely possible.
 

00:47:41.989 --> 00:47:44.360
We don't know who the author
was.

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:47.679
Wait, is this the one
that--what's the one that

00:47:47.679 --> 00:47:51.793
Tertullian says up--okay he
knew--we actually know that it

00:47:51.793 --> 00:47:54.320
was written by a priest,
right?

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:55.239
Student:  Yes.
 

00:47:55.239 --> 00:47:56.931
Prof: This one wasn't
written by a woman,

00:47:56.931 --> 00:47:59.018
but for some of the text in the
ancient world they could be

00:47:59.018 --> 00:48:00.585
written by--
Student:  Not everyone

00:48:00.585 --> 00:48:01.280
